Attitude and Heading Reference System.

The block outputs orientation and bias-corrected angular velocity from IMU measurements. Tune the measurement noises to match a specific sensor. Tune the environmental noises to match the motion characteristics.

Convert to a specified coordinate transformation representation.

The input and output coordinate transformations may be specified as the representations listed below, where all vectors must be column vectors:

  • Axis-Angle (AxAng): [x y z theta]
  • Euler Angles (Eul): [z y x], [z y z], or [x y z]
  • Homogeneous Transformation (TForm): [4x4] matrix
  • Quaternion (Quat): [w x y z]
  • Rotation Matrix (RotM): [3x3] matrix
  • Translation Vector (TrVec): [x y z]

Set the desired Representation parameter for both the Input and Output coordinate transformations.

Simulate accelerometer, gyroscope, and magnetometer sensors.

The block outputs sensor measurements based on device motion. The inputs are in the local navigation frame. The outputs are in the local sensor body frame. The parameters on the Accelerometer, Gyroscope and Magnetometer tabs can be set to match values on a sensor datasheet.

Compute linear and angular velocity control commands for following a path using a set of waypoints and the current pose of a differential drive robot.

The input port Pose accepts a three-element state vector of xy-positions and vehicle heading, [x y theta]. The input port Waypoints accepts an N-by-2 matrix as xy-coordinates. The output ports Linear Velocity and Angular Velocity return linear and angular velocities as scalar values, respectively. The Target Direction port outputs an angle with respect to the forward direction of the robot with positive angles measured counter-clockwise. 

Set the Lookahead distance to tune how closely the robot follows the path. A smaller Lookahead distance improves path tracking but can lead to instability.
